1
00:00:07,011 --> 00:00:09,138
So, you want to be a
secretary for a talent manager.

2
00:00:09,222 --> 00:00:11,766
-Yes. Very much.
-Great.

3
00:00:12,767 --> 00:00:14,769
You're up.

4
00:00:14,853 --> 00:00:16,646
-Excuse me?
-Go ahead. I'm all ears.

5
00:00:16,730 --> 00:00:19,733
Oh. Well, what would you like to know?

6
00:00:20,817 --> 00:00:22,736
Give me a minute.

7
00:00:28,992 --> 00:00:32,370
Do you have a natural flair
for meticulous organization?

8
00:00:32,454 --> 00:00:33,788
I'd say yes. Yes, I do.

9
00:00:33,872 --> 00:00:35,957
Great.

10
00:00:38,918 --> 00:00:40,920
You excuse me again?

11
00:00:46,885 --> 00:00:49,804
Can you always be depended
upon to do what you say you'll do?

12
00:00:49,888 --> 00:00:52,138
-Yes, certainly.
-Fantastic. [CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

13
00:00:54,100 --> 00:00:55,768
Perhaps you'd like to see my résumé?

14
00:00:55,852 --> 00:00:58,396
Excellent, yes, let's take a gander.

15
00:00:58,480 --> 00:01:00,398
Three pages, huh?

16
00:01:00,482 --> 00:01:01,649
-Mm-hmm.
-[SNORTS]

17
00:01:01,733 --> 00:01:04,068
Come on. Some of this is bullshit, right?

18
00:01:04,152 --> 00:01:05,403
Then I went to Brooklyn College,

19
00:01:05,487 --> 00:01:06,946
where I got my BA in English literature.

20
00:01:07,030 --> 00:01:08,531
Very good.

21
00:01:08,615 --> 00:01:11,534
And… why do you want to work here?

22
00:01:11,618 --> 00:01:13,536
Many reasons.
But first and foremost, I'm excited

23
00:01:13,620 --> 00:01:15,371
to get in on the ground
floor of a growing business.

24
00:01:15,455 --> 00:01:16,831
Growing business.

25
00:01:16,915 --> 00:01:19,834
Okay, that's putting a
shit-ton of pressure on me.

26
00:01:19,918 --> 00:01:22,086
Do you have any questions
you'd like to ask me?

27
00:01:22,170 --> 00:01:24,547
Um, what will a typical
workday look like?

28
00:01:24,631 --> 00:01:28,092
Will you excuse me a minute?

29
00:01:29,093 --> 00:01:30,511
Every one of these broads, they can type,

30
00:01:30,595 --> 00:01:33,849
they graduated from
someplace, they sit nice.

31
00:01:33,933 --> 00:01:36,393
I got this book with questions to ask.
It's no fucking help.

32
00:01:36,477 --> 00:01:37,978
All the girls give the same answer,

33
00:01:38,062 --> 00:01:39,855
because they all probably
got a fucking book, too.

34
00:01:39,939 --> 00:01:41,398
You ever hire anybody?

35
00:01:41,482 --> 00:01:42,733
-Sure, lots of people.
<i>-Well, what kind of stuff</i>

36
00:01:42,817 --> 00:01:43,942
<i>do you ask, so you know who to pick?</i>

37
00:01:44,026 --> 00:01:45,861
That depends.
You got to tailor the questions

38
00:01:45,945 --> 00:01:47,112
to the specific job.

39
00:01:47,196 --> 00:01:48,405
Yeah. How, Fred? How?

40
00:01:48,489 --> 00:01:50,407
Well, when I hired a guy
to paint my apartment,

41
00:01:50,491 --> 00:01:52,576
-I asked if he had a ten-foot ladder.
<i>-Okay.</i>

42
00:01:52,660 --> 00:01:54,870
But I didn't ask that
when I hired my tax guy

43
00:01:54,954 --> 00:01:57,122
<i>or the girl to get my
brother laid after his divorce.</i>

44
00:01:57,206 --> 00:01:58,874
<i>You don't need a ladder for those jobs.</i>

45
00:01:58,958 --> 00:02:01,418
Fred, did you ever hire
anybody at William Morris

46
00:02:01,502 --> 00:02:03,837
in a professional,
show-business capacity?

47
00:02:03,921 --> 00:02:05,005
Not per se.

48
00:02:05,089 --> 00:02:06,173
-I'm hanging up.
<i>-Wait.</i>

49
00:02:06,257 --> 00:02:08,467
You should definitely
see how the person chews.

50
00:02:08,551 --> 00:02:10,177
<i>-What?</i>
-I'm serious.

51
00:02:10,261 --> 00:02:12,137
You're going to be in
close quarters with this girl,

52
00:02:12,221 --> 00:02:14,973
with snacks and whatnot,
munching and crunching,

53
00:02:15,057 --> 00:02:16,183
<i>day in, day out.</i>

54
00:02:16,267 --> 00:02:19,019
<i>If they chew loud, you're doomed.</i>

55
00:02:19,103 --> 00:02:21,146
My shorthand is excellent,
and I type 70 words per minute.

56
00:02:21,230 --> 00:02:23,190
-Mm-hmm.
-I'm friendly but I'm firm.

57
00:02:23,274 --> 00:02:25,150
Your time is precious,
and I'll be the gatekeeper.

58
00:02:25,234 --> 00:02:27,194
There will be no
unwarranted interruptions.

59
00:02:27,278 --> 00:02:30,280
Yes, that is all very interesting.

60
00:02:30,364 --> 00:02:32,324
Hey, you hungry?

61
00:02:32,408 --> 00:02:34,618
-Uh, no, not really.
-'Cause I was about to eat this, but now

62
00:02:34,702 --> 00:02:35,786
why don't you have it?

63
00:02:35,870 --> 00:02:37,454
Thank you, no, I just had lunch.

64
00:02:37,538 --> 00:02:38,914
I'll cut it up for you.
I got a pocketknife.

65
00:02:38,998 --> 00:02:40,165
That's very nice, but really, no.

66
00:02:40,249 --> 00:02:41,625
Oh, come on, it's nice and crispy.

67
00:02:41,709 --> 00:02:43,168
To be honest, I'm actually allergic…

68
00:02:43,252 --> 00:02:44,753
Eat the fucking apple!

69
00:02:44,837 --> 00:02:46,463
♪♪

70
00:02:59,184 --> 00:03:00,477
[FRUSTRATED GRUNT]

71
00:03:09,278 --> 00:03:10,904
-Papa, are you up?
-Who is it?

72
00:03:10,988 --> 00:03:12,239
It's me, Abe.

73
00:03:12,323 --> 00:03:14,074
-It's not you.
-[KNOCKING]

74
00:03:14,158 --> 00:03:17,619
-Stop that, please.
-It's not me.

75
00:03:17,703 --> 00:03:19,079
Did I wake you?

76
00:03:19,163 --> 00:03:20,956
Sorry, I figured you'd be reading.

77
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:22,958
Your mother made me turn out my light.

78
00:03:23,042 --> 00:03:24,376
Now, what is it?

79
00:03:24,460 --> 00:03:26,378
I need some help, but
I'll ask you tomorrow.

80
00:03:26,462 --> 00:03:28,088
No, it's fine. I was just lying there

81
00:03:28,172 --> 00:03:30,048
thinking about how she
made me turn out my light.

82
00:03:30,132 --> 00:03:32,092
I just can't get my checkbook to balance,

83
00:03:32,176 --> 00:03:34,344
-and it's driving me crazy.
-What's going on?

84
00:03:34,428 --> 00:03:36,096
Nothing.
Miriam can't balance her checkbook.

85
00:03:36,180 --> 00:03:38,056
Why on earth would
you have her doing that

86
00:03:38,140 --> 00:03:40,517
-in the middle of the night, Abe?
-I live in a Dr. Seuss book.

87
00:03:40,601 --> 00:03:42,269
I'm sorry I got you up.
Back to bed, you two.

88
00:03:42,353 --> 00:03:42,718
Night night.

89
00:03:42,802 --> 00:03:44,354
I can't sleep when your
father's just lying there

90
00:03:44,438 --> 00:03:46,398
thinking about how I
made him turn out the light.

91
00:03:46,482 --> 00:03:48,692
-Then let me turn on my light.
-Fine, I'll sleep on the couch.

92
00:03:48,776 --> 00:03:51,069
Do not sleep on the couch.
It wears out the cushions faster

93
00:03:51,153 --> 00:03:55,240
-than just everyday sitting.
-Then I'm going back to bed.

94
00:03:55,324 --> 00:03:57,284
[SIGHS] Where's the checkbook?

95
00:03:57,368 --> 00:03:58,827
In the kitchen.

96
00:03:58,911 --> 00:04:00,871
It's been weeks.
You have to stop fighting.

97
00:04:00,955 --> 00:04:02,831
Who's fighting? I'm simply recalibrating

98
00:04:02,915 --> 00:04:04,833
my entire relationship with your mother

99
00:04:04,917 --> 00:04:07,085
based on information she
previously chose to keep secret

100
00:04:07,169 --> 00:04:08,587
for 35 years.

101
00:04:08,671 --> 00:04:11,131
Okay. Could you stop that, then?

102
00:04:11,215 --> 00:04:13,133
It comes out different every time.

103
00:04:13,217 --> 00:04:15,678
-Always terrible but never the same.
-Ugh.

104
00:04:16,762 --> 00:04:18,138
What's this?

105
00:04:18,222 --> 00:04:20,098
Is it better if it's a one or a seven?

106
00:04:20,182 --> 00:04:21,975
It's less bad if it's a seven.

107
00:04:22,059 --> 00:04:23,727
Call it a seven.

108
00:04:23,811 --> 00:04:25,687
And this is what you're getting paid

109
00:04:25,771 --> 00:04:27,898
for selling all that Tupperware?

110
00:04:27,982 --> 00:04:30,275
It's no way to get rich,
but I did win an aquarium.

111
00:04:30,359 --> 00:04:32,986
Which has been surprisingly
expensive to maintain.

112
00:04:33,070 --> 00:04:36,282
I sold the most pastel
Wonderliers in my region.

113
00:04:36,366 --> 00:04:36,769
Mm-hmm.

114
00:04:36,853 --> 00:04:39,452
I also won those toasters
and a salad spinner.

115
00:04:39,536 --> 00:04:41,287
And surely you've seen
the two large dalmatians

116
00:04:41,371 --> 00:04:42,830
in our living room.

117
00:04:42,914 --> 00:04:46,918
Do you think Joel could
try to contribute a little more?

118
00:04:47,002 --> 00:04:49,462
He's doing everything he can, Papa.

119
00:04:49,546 --> 00:04:50,714
[SIGHS] Well…

120
00:04:51,798 --> 00:04:53,633
There's your balance.

121
00:04:53,717 --> 00:04:56,052
Uh, that's if the number was a seven.

122
00:04:56,136 --> 00:04:58,638
And that's if it was a one.

123
00:04:58,722 --> 00:05:01,140
I think even Ethan could have helped you.

124
00:05:01,224 --> 00:05:05,061
Thanks, Papa. Really.

125
00:05:05,145 --> 00:05:07,647
Could I bring my book in here and read?

126
00:05:07,731 --> 00:05:09,482
Sure.

127
00:05:09,566 --> 00:05:12,026
I'll forgive your mother in the morning.

128
00:05:12,110 --> 00:05:14,988
For God's sake, the woman
owns a Chanel sleep mask.

129
00:05:19,325 --> 00:05:21,327
[PHONE RINGING]

130
00:05:23,413 --> 00:05:25,415
[RINGING CONTINUES]

131
00:05:29,377 --> 00:05:31,212
Looks like it's gonna be four debates.

132
00:05:31,296 --> 00:05:32,630
Kennedy-Nixon?

133
00:05:32,714 --> 00:05:34,173
-He's such a creep.
-Which one?

134
00:05:34,257 --> 00:05:36,217
Nixon. Mei.

135
00:05:36,301 --> 00:05:37,635
They both have skeletons.

136
00:05:37,719 --> 00:05:38,803
You are not voting for Nixon.

137
00:05:38,887 --> 00:05:40,513
I am not voting for Nixon.

138
00:05:40,597 --> 00:05:41,806
He looks like he eats children.

139
00:05:41,890 --> 00:05:43,099
-[RINGING CONTINUES]
-Thank you.

140
00:05:43,183 --> 00:05:44,392
-[KNOCKING]
-Ethan wants

141
00:05:44,476 --> 00:05:46,227
one of these Etch A Sketch things,

142
00:05:46,311 --> 00:05:48,688
but they're $2.99, and
he'll break it in, like, a day.

143
00:05:48,772 --> 00:05:50,106
-[KNOCKING]
-What's an Etch A Sketch?

144
00:05:50,190 --> 00:05:51,941
-[DOORBELL BUZZING]
-You draw on the screen with the knobs,

145
00:05:52,025 --> 00:05:53,725
then you shake it,
and the picture erases.

146
00:05:53,809 --> 00:05:54,819
What's the point of that?

147
00:05:54,903 --> 00:05:57,530
-[RINGING, KNOCKING, BUZZING]
-To teach kids that nothing lasts?

148
00:05:57,614 --> 00:05:58,948
-Joel!
-What?

149
00:05:59,032 --> 00:06:00,533
You're not even gonna answer the door?

150
00:06:00,617 --> 00:06:01,993
-Nah.
-Come on!

151
00:06:02,077 --> 00:06:03,703
-[BUZZING]
-We discussed this.

152
00:06:03,787 --> 00:06:05,496
It could be another one of Ma's girls.

153
00:06:05,580 --> 00:06:08,666
-If I open it, I'm as good as engaged.
-It could be a delivery.

154
00:06:08,750 --> 00:06:09,959
-They'll leave it.
-Someone could steal it.

155
00:06:10,043 --> 00:06:11,210
-[KNOCKING]
-Nothing lasts.

156
00:06:11,294 --> 00:06:12,211
What do you do at the club?

157
00:06:12,295 --> 00:06:13,379
-Shh.
-Why?

158
00:06:13,463 --> 00:06:15,006
In case they're listening at the door.

159
00:06:15,090 --> 00:06:17,216
If the phone rings at the
club, you have to answer it.

160
00:06:17,300 --> 00:06:19,260
People want to come
in, you have to let them in.

161
00:06:19,344 --> 00:06:21,429
There's a protocol for
women of childbearing age.

162
00:06:21,513 --> 00:06:23,556
If they want to talk to me,
Mrs. Moskowitz screens them

163
00:06:23,640 --> 00:06:25,141
with a series of discreet questions.

164
00:06:25,225 --> 00:06:27,143
-Oh, my God.
-The system's worked for weeks.

165
00:06:27,227 --> 00:06:29,270
-Why question it now?
-Because it's demented.

166
00:06:29,354 --> 00:06:30,813
-[PHONE RINGING]
-Because it's…

167
00:06:30,897 --> 00:06:32,523
Aah! I'll do it!

168
00:06:32,607 --> 00:06:34,275
-Do what?
-I'll meet your parents.

169
00:06:34,359 --> 00:06:35,401
Just answer the phone!

170
00:06:35,485 --> 00:06:37,862
-No. We can wait my mother out.
-We can't.

171
00:06:37,946 --> 00:06:40,281
We can. She's getting older.
She has limited wind.

172
00:06:40,365 --> 00:06:41,866
We need our lives back, Joel.

173
00:06:41,950 --> 00:06:43,826
-My life is fine.
-Well, mine isn't.

174
00:06:43,910 --> 00:06:45,411
This is dumb. I mean, you said it.

175
00:06:45,495 --> 00:06:48,039
-[PHONE RINGING]
-We're in a… a…

176
00:06:48,123 --> 00:06:49,874
Relationship.

177
00:06:49,958 --> 00:06:51,167
Yes. That. Sure.

178
00:06:51,251 --> 00:06:52,585
They have to know.

179
00:06:52,669 --> 00:06:55,755
Make a date. End the madness.

180
00:06:55,839 --> 00:06:56,839
I'll just move again.

181
00:06:56,923 --> 00:06:58,758
A moving target will confuse her.

182
00:06:58,842 --> 00:07:00,635
-[HANGS UP PHONE]
-[RINGING STOPS]

183
00:07:03,179 --> 00:07:05,014
Set it up. Today.

184
00:07:05,098 --> 00:07:07,142
I'll be at the movies.

185
00:07:10,478 --> 00:07:12,105
Just in case.

186
00:07:13,523 --> 00:07:15,024
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

187
00:07:18,403 --> 00:07:20,154
Susie? Oh. Sorry.

188
00:07:20,238 --> 00:07:22,031
I just need to talk to
you when you're done.

189
00:07:22,115 --> 00:07:23,908
-No, now's a good time.
-Should I wait outside?

190
00:07:23,992 --> 00:07:25,451
Nah. You ain't getting the job.

191
00:07:25,535 --> 00:07:27,871
-Oh. Okay, thank you.
-No. Thank you.

192
00:07:28,997 --> 00:07:31,582
-What's with your phone?
-Nothing. Why?

193
00:07:31,666 --> 00:07:34,318
I've been calling all morning.
All you get is a busy signal.

194
00:07:34,402 --> 00:07:34,628
Shit.

195
00:07:34,712 --> 00:07:36,922
You need a secretary.

196
00:07:37,006 --> 00:07:38,090
What do you think that was?

197
00:07:38,174 --> 00:07:39,800
[GRUNTS] What's up?

198
00:07:39,884 --> 00:07:41,510
-This.
-What is that?

199
00:07:41,594 --> 00:07:45,305
This is my invitation to
Shy Baldwin's wedding.

200
00:07:45,389 --> 00:07:46,890
Why the fuck would you be invited

201
00:07:46,974 --> 00:07:49,101
-to Shy Baldwin's wedding?
-You tell me.

202
00:07:49,185 --> 00:07:50,894
I don't know.
They're working off an old list?

203
00:07:50,978 --> 00:07:54,314
-Then you would've been invited.
-And I was not invited.

204
00:07:54,398 --> 00:07:56,942
-Susie.
-I guess I <i>was</i> invited.

205
00:07:57,026 --> 00:07:59,194
Why the hell was I invited
to Shy Baldwin's wedding?

206
00:07:59,278 --> 00:08:01,238
And it's three days from now.

207
00:08:01,322 --> 00:08:02,823
Basic wedding etiquette
dictates invitations go out

208
00:08:02,907 --> 00:08:05,075
45 days prior to the event, at a minimum.

209
00:08:05,159 --> 00:08:06,493
I'm sorry, you're offended
that you were invited

210
00:08:06,577 --> 00:08:08,620
at the last minute to a
wedding you don't want to go to?

211
00:08:08,704 --> 00:08:09,621
Yes. Who wouldn't be?

212
00:08:09,705 --> 00:08:11,373
-Me.
-And not only am I not going,

213
00:08:11,457 --> 00:08:13,250
I'm RSVPing "yes" and then not going,

214
00:08:13,334 --> 00:08:14,626
just to screw up his count.

215
00:08:14,710 --> 00:08:15,919
You're a monster.

216
00:08:16,003 --> 00:08:18,088
That thing's a waste
of a nice gilded edge.

217
00:08:18,172 --> 00:08:20,632
You know what? Maybe we should go.

218
00:08:20,716 --> 00:08:23,635
-Go? Are you kidding me?
-There's no way

219
00:08:23,719 --> 00:08:25,512
there's not an open bar, some good food.

220
00:08:25,596 --> 00:08:26,847
You are not serious.

221
00:08:26,931 --> 00:08:28,140
He kind of owes us, you know?

222
00:08:28,224 --> 00:08:29,349
You could get your picture taken there,

223
00:08:29,433 --> 00:08:31,810
get some good exposure
and some good cake.

224
00:08:31,894 --> 00:08:34,563
I am kind of curious to
see the whole spectacle.

225
00:08:34,647 --> 00:08:37,566
And I am really curious
to drink a lot of free booze.

226
00:08:39,610 --> 00:08:40,819
Did you see that?

227
00:08:40,903 --> 00:08:41,862
-See what?
-So you didn't?

228
00:08:41,946 --> 00:08:42,404
The smoke?

229
00:08:42,488 --> 00:08:44,156
-So you did.
-I did.

230
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:46,158
-Damn. Damn it.
-Were we not supposed to?

231
00:08:46,242 --> 00:08:48,243
Of course you were, but not then. Later.

232
00:08:48,327 --> 00:08:49,703
[YELLS]

233
00:08:49,787 --> 00:08:50,996
It's no good! I can't…

234
00:08:51,080 --> 00:08:52,539
What was I… How am I supposed…

235
00:08:52,623 --> 00:08:53,999
Breathe it out.

236
00:08:54,083 --> 00:08:56,877
It was on four, not three.
Just have to remember to count.

237
00:08:56,961 --> 00:08:59,338
[TAKES DEEP BREATH]
I'll just try it again.

238
00:09:03,592 --> 00:09:06,092
I'm looking pretty good
to you right now, aren't I?

239
00:09:08,514 --> 00:09:12,434
I got a net. I should save for Ethan?

240
00:09:12,518 --> 00:09:14,186
We have saying back home:

241
00:09:14,270 --> 00:09:17,731
"Never too early for
child to learn how to bury."

242
00:09:17,815 --> 00:09:21,735
Mm. Let's just flush him and
let his memory be a blessing.

243
00:09:21,819 --> 00:09:24,446
Do we have any matches, Zelda?
This is dangerous.

244
00:09:24,530 --> 00:09:27,574
I saw Miss Miriam has matches
in her bedroom. I'll get them.

245
00:09:28,701 --> 00:09:30,995
-[PHONE RINGING]
-I'll get it, Zelda.

246
00:09:34,331 --> 00:09:36,541
-Weissman residence.
-[WOMAN SPEAKING FAINTLY ON PHONE]

247
00:09:36,625 --> 00:09:38,627
Mm, this is she.

248
00:09:41,672 --> 00:09:43,048
Well, of course.

249
00:09:43,132 --> 00:09:45,509
I'd be very happy to
meet with Mr. Melamid.

250
00:09:46,552 --> 00:09:49,221
Certainly, any time he'd like.

251
00:09:49,305 --> 00:09:51,598
Today's fine.

252
00:09:51,682 --> 00:09:54,476
Half an hour. I can be ready by then.

253
00:09:54,560 --> 00:09:57,354
It's 385 Riverside Drive in Manhattan.

254
00:09:57,438 --> 00:09:58,647
WOMAN: <i>Thank you so much.</i>

255
00:09:58,731 --> 00:10:00,440
You're welcome. Thank you.

256
00:10:00,524 --> 00:10:01,984
<i>Goodbye.</i>

257
00:10:04,278 --> 00:10:06,613
As it turns out, I don't
have time for tea after all.

258
00:10:06,697 --> 00:10:08,615
There's a car coming for me.

259
00:10:08,699 --> 00:10:10,617
I have business in Scarsdale.

260
00:10:10,701 --> 00:10:12,953
Please tell Mr. Weissman
when he comes home.

261
00:10:13,037 --> 00:10:16,665
Okay, I'll tell him you went
outside to do your business.

262
00:10:17,750 --> 00:10:19,751
I'll just leave a note.

263
00:10:19,835 --> 00:10:21,670
[DORIS DAY: "NICE
WORK IF YOU CAN GET IT"]

264
00:10:21,754 --> 00:10:25,382
<i>♪ Holding hands at midnight ♪</i>

265
00:10:25,466 --> 00:10:29,053
<i>♪ 'Neath the starry sky ♪</i>

266
00:10:30,471 --> 00:10:33,265
<i>♪ Nice work if you can get ♪</i>

267
00:10:33,349 --> 00:10:34,933
<i>♪ And you can get it ♪</i>

268
00:10:35,017 --> 00:10:36,476
<i>♪ If you try ♪</i>

269
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:38,354
-Just over there, ma'am.
-Thank you.

270
00:10:38,438 --> 00:10:41,941
<i>-♪ Strolling with… ♪</i>
-Mrs. Weissman.

271
00:10:42,025 --> 00:10:44,235
Solomon Melamid.

272
00:10:44,319 --> 00:10:46,404
I'd, uh, shake your hand, but mine is

273
00:10:46,488 --> 00:10:48,233
straight from the horse's
mouth, shall we say.

274
00:10:48,317 --> 00:10:48,698
[LAUGHS]

275
00:10:48,782 --> 00:10:50,283
-Anyway, welcome.
-Rose Weissman.

276
00:10:50,367 --> 00:10:51,659
-[NEIGHS]
-It's a pleasure.

277
00:10:51,743 --> 00:10:53,286
Cut it out, Zephaniah.

278
00:10:53,370 --> 00:10:54,829
Don't let him scare you.

279
00:10:54,913 --> 00:10:57,123
Oh, it takes more than a
little showing off to do that.

280
00:10:57,207 --> 00:10:59,709
I grew up with horses. In Oklahoma.

281
00:10:59,793 --> 00:11:01,961
-And I see you wore sensible shoes.
-Well, there's nothing elegant

282
00:11:02,045 --> 00:11:04,380
about landing on your
backside in the mud, is there?

283
00:11:04,464 --> 00:11:06,549
I can tell, you know a thing or two.

284
00:11:06,633 --> 00:11:07,967
Join me in a walk?

285
00:11:08,051 --> 00:11:09,677
-[LOUD NEIGHING]
-Now, that…

286
00:11:09,761 --> 00:11:10,845
MAN: Whoa, boy!

287
00:11:10,929 --> 00:11:13,723
…is Copper Jack, my prize stallion.

288
00:11:13,807 --> 00:11:17,018
A stable boy walked a mare
past his stall this morning.

289
00:11:17,102 --> 00:11:19,103
Poor devil got a whiff,
and he hasn't been able

290
00:11:19,187 --> 00:11:21,814
-to calm himself since.
-Hmm. Your house, my goodness,

291
00:11:21,898 --> 00:11:24,984
it's even more stunning than
it looked in <i>Town & Country.</i>

292
00:11:25,068 --> 00:11:27,153
My great-grandfather
had it built in 1840.

293
00:11:27,237 --> 00:11:29,322
We throw on another
wing from time to time

294
00:11:29,406 --> 00:11:30,990
birthdays, Hanukkah.

295
00:11:31,074 --> 00:11:32,992
Hmm, your family's in
the railroad business.

296
00:11:33,076 --> 00:11:35,995
Railroad, shipping, steel.
We're eyeing aviation.

297
00:11:36,079 --> 00:11:38,456
Innovation's key. Stagnation is death.

298
00:11:38,540 --> 00:11:40,458
You're a businesswoman;
you know all this.

299
00:11:40,542 --> 00:11:42,710
-Oh, yes, I am. I do.
-[CHUCKLES]

300
00:11:42,794 --> 00:11:44,545
Mrs. Weissman, I wanted to meet you,

301
00:11:44,629 --> 00:11:48,049
because your impressive
match for my lawyer's daughter

302
00:11:48,133 --> 00:11:49,884
did not escape my notice.

303
00:11:49,968 --> 00:11:51,719
Norma and Lorraine, my two daughters,

304
00:11:51,803 --> 00:11:54,055
are 31 and 32 years old.

305
00:11:54,139 --> 00:11:55,056
Oh!

306
00:11:55,140 --> 00:11:57,183
-Uh, sorry.
-No, don't be.

307
00:11:57,267 --> 00:11:59,185
Their mother cries
herself to sleep every night

308
00:11:59,269 --> 00:12:00,895
wondering where she went wrong.

309
00:12:00,979 --> 00:12:02,730
Well, you've come to the right place.

310
00:12:02,814 --> 00:12:04,565
Trees with a few more rings on them

311
00:12:04,649 --> 00:12:06,609
happen to be a specialty of mine.

312
00:12:06,693 --> 00:12:07,610
-Really?
-Mm-hmm.

313
00:12:07,694 --> 00:12:08,778
That's good to hear.

314
00:12:08,862 --> 00:12:10,071
[LOUD NEIGHING]

315
00:12:10,155 --> 00:12:11,739
I think we're gonna
have to give him Starlight

316
00:12:11,823 --> 00:12:13,157
just to calm him down.

317
00:12:13,241 --> 00:12:15,368
Horses are easy.

318
00:12:15,452 --> 00:12:17,161
You throw them together, a little noise,

319
00:12:17,245 --> 00:12:20,498
maybe a stall door needs
repairing, and that's that.

320
00:12:20,582 --> 00:12:22,625
If only it were as simple with daughters.

321
00:12:22,709 --> 00:12:25,503
-Tell me about them, your girls.
-Well…

322
00:12:25,587 --> 00:12:27,505
Norma has a penchant for stable boys.

323
00:12:27,589 --> 00:12:29,632
-She's the Starlight of the family.
-I see.

324
00:12:29,716 --> 00:12:31,759
Lorraine, the younger one,
she got kicked in the head

325
00:12:31,843 --> 00:12:34,178
by a horse as a child,
so she's an easy mark.

326
00:12:34,262 --> 00:12:36,639
We've had a lot of schemers
and gigolos who look at Lorraine

327
00:12:36,723 --> 00:12:38,808
and see the goose
that laid the golden egg.

328
00:12:38,892 --> 00:12:41,352
-[CHUCKLES] She almost married an actor.
-Heavens.

329
00:12:41,436 --> 00:12:44,897
I got him a job on the road
promoting Ford Thunderbirds.

330
00:12:44,981 --> 00:12:47,066
He's in Alaska as we speak.

331
00:12:47,150 --> 00:12:49,360
But they aren't all
so easily disposed of.

332
00:12:49,444 --> 00:12:51,404
You just need someone
to screen out the schemers

333
00:12:51,488 --> 00:12:53,406
and find the man who will love Lorraine

334
00:12:53,490 --> 00:12:55,533
for who she is and not what she has.

335
00:12:55,617 --> 00:12:57,827
And I need to be able to
bring my daughters' husbands

336
00:12:57,911 --> 00:12:59,912
into the family business.
They can't be idiots,

337
00:12:59,996 --> 00:13:02,498
-or obvious idiots.
-Well, Mr. Melamid,

338
00:13:02,582 --> 00:13:04,792
I assure you I can find
some very nice men

339
00:13:04,876 --> 00:13:06,544
who are not obviously idiots

340
00:13:06,628 --> 00:13:08,921
and will make Norma
and Lorraine very happy.

341
00:13:09,005 --> 00:13:10,131
Oh, yes.

342
00:13:10,215 --> 00:13:12,133
Happy, that would be good, too.

343
00:13:12,217 --> 00:13:14,427
Not a deal breaker, but a nice bonus.

344
00:13:14,511 --> 00:13:16,554
Mrs. Weissman, I am appointing you

345
00:13:16,638 --> 00:13:20,099
director of the nearly bankrupt
division of Melamid Industries

346
00:13:20,183 --> 00:13:22,560
known as my daughters' marital prospects.

347
00:13:22,644 --> 00:13:24,520
Good luck. And if it's any incentive,

348
00:13:24,604 --> 00:13:28,399
the extended Melamid family
is large, rich and homely,

349
00:13:28,483 --> 00:13:31,444
so there could be a lot of
Melamid matches in your future.

350
00:13:31,528 --> 00:13:33,446
Well, then I'd better get right to work.

351
00:13:33,530 --> 00:13:35,573
Where are Norma and Lorraine now?

352
00:13:35,657 --> 00:13:36,657
In the city.

353
00:13:36,741 --> 00:13:38,451
They live together there
like a pair of ex-nuns.

354
00:13:38,535 --> 00:13:40,579
I'll set up meetings right
away to get to know them.

355
00:13:40,663 --> 00:13:43,290
Please tell Mrs. Melamid I
said she should start thinking

356
00:13:43,374 --> 00:13:44,666
about the centerpieces.

357
00:13:44,750 --> 00:13:46,168
One more thing.

358
00:13:46,252 --> 00:13:48,170
Respectability is of
the utmost importance

359
00:13:48,254 --> 00:13:49,421
to the Melamid family.

360
00:13:49,505 --> 00:13:52,716
We value decency, dignity and discretion,

361
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:55,886
and we assume you
and your family do as well.

362
00:13:55,970 --> 00:13:58,472
-Yes, of course, Mr. Melamid.
-Good.

363
00:13:58,556 --> 00:14:00,474
Call me Solomon.

364
00:14:00,558 --> 00:14:01,850
John!

365
00:14:01,934 --> 00:14:04,603
Send Edgar to give Mrs. Weissman a tour.

366
00:14:04,687 --> 00:14:06,146
Make sure you see the swans.

367
00:14:06,230 --> 00:14:08,857
They are bastards but they are beautiful.

368
00:14:14,613 --> 00:14:16,323
[DOOR CLOSES]

369
00:14:16,407 --> 00:14:18,492
Hello?

370
00:14:18,576 --> 00:14:20,703
Is anybody home?

371
00:14:21,745 --> 00:14:23,455
Miriam?

372
00:14:23,539 --> 00:14:25,624
MAN [IN DISTANCE]: Ice
cream, get your ice cream here.

373
00:14:25,708 --> 00:14:26,750
[CHILDREN'S CHATTER IN DISTANCE]

374
00:14:26,834 --> 00:14:29,461
MAN: I got chocolate, I got vanilla.

375
00:14:29,545 --> 00:14:31,547
[MAN CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY]

376
00:14:57,489 --> 00:14:59,539
[CHILDREN'S CHATTER
CONTINUES IN DISTANCE]

377
00:15:12,588 --> 00:15:15,674
<i>♪ Bop, bop, bop, bop,
ba-dop, bop, bop, bop, bop ♪</i>

378
00:15:15,758 --> 00:15:19,511
<i>♪ She was afraid to
come out of the locker ♪</i>

379
00:15:19,595 --> 00:15:23,515
<i>♪ She was as nervous as she could be ♪</i>

380
00:15:23,599 --> 00:15:25,267
<i>♪ She was afraid to come out… ♪</i>

381
00:15:25,351 --> 00:15:28,270
-You're late.
-It's my chauffeur. He fired himself.

382
00:15:28,354 --> 00:15:30,397
[WHISPERS] I had to take a cab.

383
00:15:30,481 --> 00:15:32,274
-Okay, so…
-Did you hear what I said?

384
00:15:32,358 --> 00:15:34,109
A taxicab.

385
00:15:34,193 --> 00:15:37,571
Susie… I'm exhausted.

386
00:15:37,655 --> 00:15:38,947
I had to hail it myself.

387
00:15:39,031 --> 00:15:41,116
I had to put my arm up in the air,

388
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:44,369
I had to leave it there
until the cab pulled over.

389
00:15:44,453 --> 00:15:47,289
I had to open my own door.
I had to duck down…

390
00:15:47,373 --> 00:15:49,249
It sounds harrowing, but it's over.
Now focus.

391
00:15:49,333 --> 00:15:50,667
-Mm.
-Look over there.

392
00:15:50,751 --> 00:15:53,962
That is Mike Carr.
He books <i>The Gordon Ford Show.</i>

393
00:15:54,046 --> 00:15:56,089
Hmm, not unattractive.

394
00:15:56,173 --> 00:15:58,383
You are not gonna fuck him.
You're gonna meet with him.

395
00:15:58,467 --> 00:16:00,427
Now, I got to make sure
you are ready for this.

396
00:16:00,511 --> 00:16:02,262
Let me see your eyes.

397
00:16:02,346 --> 00:16:04,264
Well, at least they're
spinning in the same direction.

398
00:16:04,348 --> 00:16:06,266
Did you take your meds,
or stop taking them,

399
00:16:06,350 --> 00:16:09,102
-whichever makes you less nuts?
-Yes, both.

400
00:16:09,186 --> 00:16:11,438
Because if you screw
this up, all that's left for you

401
00:16:11,522 --> 00:16:14,566
is to be my secretary, and
you'd be a lousy secretary.

402
00:16:14,650 --> 00:16:16,151
Now, come on.

403
00:16:17,361 --> 00:16:20,989
<i>♪ It was an itsy-bitsy,
teeny-weeny yellow polka-dot… ♪</i>

404
00:16:21,073 --> 00:16:22,866
Mike Carr? Susie Myerson.

405
00:16:22,950 --> 00:16:24,868
Finally. I was about to leave.

406
00:16:24,952 --> 00:16:26,453
You would've missed out
on the meeting of a lifetime.

407
00:16:26,537 --> 00:16:29,164
When I went to a
bullfight with Hemingway,

408
00:16:29,248 --> 00:16:30,874
that was the meeting of a lifetime.

409
00:16:30,958 --> 00:16:32,626
I don't know what the fuck this is.

410
00:16:32,710 --> 00:16:35,045
Then, let me introduce you
to the goddamn living legend,

411
00:16:35,129 --> 00:16:36,838
Sophie Lennon. Sophie, Mike.

412
00:16:36,922 --> 00:16:38,006
I started out with ten minutes for you.

413
00:16:38,090 --> 00:16:39,883
I waited seven, so now I have three.

414
00:16:39,967 --> 00:16:41,969
-I like him.
-Great. Sit.

415
00:16:43,221 --> 00:16:45,723
Ooh! [GROANS]

416
00:16:45,807 --> 00:16:47,016
You okay?

417
00:16:47,100 --> 00:16:49,185
Have you ever taken a cab?

418
00:16:49,269 --> 00:16:50,645
Ignore her.

419
00:16:50,729 --> 00:16:52,438
Mike, when's your birthday?

420
00:16:52,522 --> 00:16:54,774
Day before Christmas.
It's a fucking curse.

421
00:16:54,858 --> 00:16:56,067
How would you like it to be next week?

422
00:16:56,151 --> 00:16:57,610
What's the angle here?

423
00:16:57,694 --> 00:16:59,320
I thought you said no sex.

424
00:16:59,404 --> 00:17:01,489
What I am offering you today is a gift.

425
00:17:01,573 --> 00:17:04,200
An unprecedented interview
with the great Sophie Lennon.

426
00:17:04,284 --> 00:17:05,785
Unprecedented?

427
00:17:05,869 --> 00:17:07,662
She's been on every goddamn
talk show in the country.

428
00:17:07,746 --> 00:17:09,622
I have. I've been on <i>Sullivan</i> nine times.

429
00:17:09,706 --> 00:17:11,666
Yeah, I heard about
you being "on Sullivan."

430
00:17:11,750 --> 00:17:13,376
He said he was leaving his wife.

431
00:17:13,460 --> 00:17:15,211
I am not talking about
some run-of-the-mill interview.

432
00:17:15,295 --> 00:17:16,504
Is that what you think Gordon does?

433
00:17:16,588 --> 00:17:18,047
Run-of-the-mill interviews?

434
00:17:18,131 --> 00:17:20,883
-[CHUCKLING] Mike.
-Keep walking.

435
00:17:20,967 --> 00:17:22,760
-Mike, listen…
-There's no heat on her.

436
00:17:22,844 --> 00:17:24,929
Okay?
It'd be like booking an iceberg, sorry.

437
00:17:25,013 --> 00:17:27,348
-And I accept your apology.
-Don't talk.

438
00:17:28,600 --> 00:17:30,226
Mike, just listen to me. This woman here,

439
00:17:30,310 --> 00:17:31,769
she had a nervous breakdown.

440
00:17:31,853 --> 00:17:33,396
-That's your pitch?
-She went from being

441
00:17:33,480 --> 00:17:35,189
the highest-paid
comedian in this business

442
00:17:35,273 --> 00:17:37,400
to a punch line herself
in one fucking night.

443
00:17:37,484 --> 00:17:38,901
Complete career suicide.

444
00:17:38,985 --> 00:17:40,528
You telling me that
story doesn't interest you?

445
00:17:40,612 --> 00:17:42,947
Well, sure, but we can't talk
about that shit on the show.

446
00:17:43,031 --> 00:17:44,532
-Why not?
-Because you can't.

447
00:17:44,616 --> 00:17:45,783
Who says?

448
00:17:45,867 --> 00:17:48,202
I don't know, uh… America?

449
00:17:48,286 --> 00:17:49,787
Fuck America.

450
00:17:49,871 --> 00:17:51,706
You book Sophie on that
show, she will give Gordon

451
00:17:51,790 --> 00:17:53,416
the kind of interview no other star

452
00:17:53,500 --> 00:17:55,209
in her right mind would ever agree to.

453
00:17:55,293 --> 00:17:57,253
I am not in my right mind, that is true.

454
00:17:57,337 --> 00:17:59,547
-She's got stories, Mike.
-So?

455
00:17:59,631 --> 00:18:01,674
My mother has stories.
I wouldn't book her, either.

456
00:18:01,758 --> 00:18:04,135
Who'd you have on the
show last night, Mike?

457
00:18:04,219 --> 00:18:06,512
Let me answer that… a blond starlet

458
00:18:06,596 --> 00:18:08,389
and a boring-ass director.

459
00:18:08,473 --> 00:18:09,974
The night before that,
a red-headed starlet

460
00:18:10,058 --> 00:18:11,726
and a boring-ass novelist.

461
00:18:11,810 --> 00:18:13,561
And they're all plugging something.

462
00:18:13,645 --> 00:18:15,813
They talk about their shitty
movie or their boring book,

463
00:18:15,897 --> 00:18:18,274
how everyone they work with is a genius

464
00:18:18,358 --> 00:18:20,443
and how everybody in
Hollywood is best friends.

465
00:18:20,527 --> 00:18:22,737
And maybe they throw in
a semi-embarrassing story

466
00:18:22,821 --> 00:18:24,530
about getting locked out of their house,

467
00:18:24,614 --> 00:18:26,282
wearing only a towel, then you go

468
00:18:26,366 --> 00:18:27,700
to a commercial, sell some cigarettes.

469
00:18:27,784 --> 00:18:30,119
Well, Sophie Lennon has fuck-all to plug.

470
00:18:30,203 --> 00:18:31,996
She's got nothing to lose.

471
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:35,416
So she is gonna open up
her walk-in closet of skeletons

472
00:18:35,500 --> 00:18:38,586
and introduce them all
to the world in living color.

473
00:18:38,670 --> 00:18:40,004
And her publicist isn't gonna stop her

474
00:18:40,088 --> 00:18:41,589
'cause her publicist quit last week.

475
00:18:41,673 --> 00:18:43,841
It's risky.

476
00:18:43,925 --> 00:18:45,718
If it's a disaster, I'm
the one that goes down.

477
00:18:45,802 --> 00:18:48,179
Gordon's been stuck at
number two since the beginning.

478
00:18:48,263 --> 00:18:50,306
He does something ballsy like this?

479
00:18:50,390 --> 00:18:52,183
He's number one and you're the one

480
00:18:52,267 --> 00:18:53,768
who made him number one.

481
00:18:53,852 --> 00:18:55,603
If it doesn't work, sure, it's your ass.

482
00:18:55,687 --> 00:18:58,314
But if he stays number two,
aren't you getting fired anyway?

483
00:18:58,398 --> 00:18:59,774
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

484
00:18:59,858 --> 00:19:01,317
Give me a card.

485
00:19:01,401 --> 00:19:03,194
Got one right here.

486
00:19:03,278 --> 00:19:05,572
Uh, wait, I got a…
[CLEARS THROAT] new number.

487
00:19:07,615 --> 00:19:10,326
And the printer fucked up.
There's no "Q" in "Myerson."

488
00:19:10,410 --> 00:19:12,412
Stay by your phone.

489
00:19:14,622 --> 00:19:16,791
